{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_iotite_ver01/data/sn84020064/00542866408/1930030801/0001.xml":{"full_text":"Weather\nArizona Mostly fair Saturday and\nSunday: little change in tempera\nture.\nDouglas: The maximum tempera\nture recorded here Friday was 82\ndegrees and the minimum was 34.\nVOL. XXVII.\nIndustry and Business Recover; Unemployment to End\nSolon Coalition\nLoses to G. O. P.\nAnti Bloc Overcome in Fight on Cement Tariff, But\nCounter With Demand for Another Ballot on\nSugar Hike; Charges of \u201cTrading\u201d Are Made by\nFree-Traders As Republicans Win.\nWASHINGTON. March 7\n(API The calition of demo\ncrats and republican inde\npendents suffered another\nmajor reverse in the senate\ntariff contesttoday with the ap\nproval of a duty on cement, but\nthey immediately countered with\na demand for another ballot on\nthe sugar increase.\nSenator Nye. republican inde\npendent, North Dakota, moved the\nreconsideration of both duties after\napproval had been given by a vote\nof 45 to 37 to a proposal of Senator\nKean, republican. New Jersey, to\nReichsbank Head\nQuits; Act May\nHurt Young Plan\nc\nAffect of Resignation\nMay Be Far-Reaching;\nMartyr to Beliefs.\nBERLIN, March 7. W>\u2014The resig\nnation today of Dr. Hjalmar\nSchacht as president of the Reichs\nbank is expected to have an influ\nence on the progress of the Young\nplan and its connected legislation\u2014\nthe Polish liquidation agreement\nin parliament.\nWhile at the moment the align\nment of parties to both of these is\nsues cannot be foretold, it is widely\nbelieved that Dr. Schacht's dramatic\nresignation may spur the German\npeople to induce all parties at least\nto give the Young plan and the\nPolish agreement a final and fear\nful scrutiny.\nPlan Distorted?\nFor after all Dr. Schacht, in giv\ning his reasons for resignation, re\niterated only the opinion that has\nbeen heard many times in Germany\nsince the last Hague conference\nthat the present version of the\nYoung plan is a mere distortion of\nthe original plan.\nIn Wilhelmstrasse circles it was\nbelieved the resignation would not\naffect the vote on the Young plan,\nbut political leaders agreed it came\nat an embarrassing moment. They\ndid not blame Dr. Schacht, however,\nbut rather the slowness of parlia\nmentary procedure. Under the\nschedule the second reading of the\nYoung plan should have taken place\nyesterday and Dr. Schacht had\nagreed to withhold the announce\nment of his resignation until after\na vote had been taken. But he de\ncided today to hold off no longer.\nGiven Tribute\nSince ft is widely conceded that\nDr. Schacht is one of the outstand\ning men in Germany, his resigna\ntion created a feeling of country\nwide stupefaction. The boerse first\nreacted with a panicky movement\nbut the majority ot shares soon\nrallied.\n(Continued on Page Five)\nArmored Rum Ship\nIs Taken in Chase\nWarning Shots Fail to\nHalt Craft; Liquor and\nBeer Are Seized.\nLORAIN. Ohio. March 7 (45-\nOne of the largest rum boats on the\nGreat Lakes, a 65-foot armored\nmotor-cruiser, its cargo of 3.000\ncases of whisky and beer, and its\ncrew of two men were held here\ntonight, after a spectacular battle\nwith coast guards on Lake Erie to\nday.\nOne of the prisoners was serious\nly wounded and was taken to a\nLorain hospital. He said he was\nFred Hentrie of Detroit. The ocher\ngave the name of Joe Hanna. Coast\nguards said the rum boat is the\nSambo 0., of Port Stanley. Ont.,\nand that it had cleared from Eneau\nor Kingsville. Ontario.\nPursued For Honrs.\nThe capture was made after a\npursuit of several hours in which\nthe guardsmen showered rifle bul\nlets and one-pound sliells on the\nfugitive craft. Strips of five-eighths\ninch steel covered the boat in vul\nnerable parts, and the bullets and\nshells laded to stop it.\nTnere was no shorting frcnr< the\nrum boat but once It took the ag\ngressive and made a lull speed\ndash at Lie coast guaid boat No.\n106. The Sambo G., rammed hard\ninto the 196. hitting it amidsntps.\ntearing a large hole just* above the\nwater Une.\nDAILY\nIBouglas 33 ispatch\nTEN PAGES TODAY\nI place a levy of six cents per hun\ni died pounds on cement now on the\nfree list In January the coalition\nput cement back on the free list by\na vote of 40 to 35.\nSees \u201cAgreement\u201d\n\u201cI am forced at this time to re\nmark that none are so blind as\n.those who will not see.\u201d Nye as\n[ssrted. Although he voted on both\noccasions that sugar was under con\nsideration for an increased tariff,\nthe Ncrth Dakotan-said he thought\u201d\nthere was some evidence ot an\nagreement\u201d this week when the\ncoalition broke and an increased\nsugar duty carried.\nThough it might not entirely be\nI shown and proved that a trade had\nbeen entered into.\u201d he added, \u201cif it\n\u2022were proved I hardly see how I\ncould escape altogether being made\na part of that trade. And I care\nnot how indirect a part I may in\nnocently appear to have been in any\ni such understanding\u2014in such a deal\n\u2014I am not going to be in any sense\na party of it. I therefore move to\nreconsider the vote of day before\nyesterday whereby an increased\nduty was levied on sugar.\u201d\nChanges Vote\nPreviously Nye. who had voted\nI against the Kean amendment,\nchanged his vote in order to move\nreconsideration of this ballot. He\nand four other senators, Couzen.s.\nMichigan, and Pine. Oklahoma, re\npublicans and Tydings. Manland, i\nand Wagner. New York, democrats,\nwere recorded in favor of the 6-cent\nrate, whereas last January they vet\ni ed for free cement as against, an 8-\ncent rate in the bill. This is the\nrate carried by the house measure\nCouzens explained before the fOT\ncall that he was changing his vote\nbecause sinc^ the January vote the\nsenate had repealed all countervail\ning duties including that of 8 cents\na hundred pounnds against Can\nadian cement, and the 6 cents was\n25 per cent less than the original\namendment for 8 cents against all\ncement.\nProducers Prosper\nSpeaking for the cement duty\nSenator Vandenber. republican,\nMichigan, also called attention to\nthe vote to repeal the countervail\ning duty against Canada which has\nbeen in effect since 1922. Under\nthis retaliatory clause, he said\n(Continued on Page Five)\n-J-,.-.- _\nWine Valued At\nI\nMillions Seized\nGovernment Padlocks\n200,000 Gallons Near\nSacramento, Calif.\nSACRAMENTO. March 7 Ori\nNearly 200.000 gallons of rare wine,\nvalued at approximately $1,000,000\nwere confiscated today by federal\nprohibition agents in a raid on the\nSilva Brothers bonded winery. 12\nmiles east of Sacramento.\nManuel I. and King Silva, broth\ners, were taken into custory and\nsubsequently released on $5,000 bond\neach by U. S. Commissioner John\nQ. Brown. Jr.\nThe federal operatives declared\nthe arrest and seizure of the entire\nwinery results from the receipt of\nnumerous complaints regarding al\nleged illicit sale of wine to unauth\norized parties.\nThe raiders, under government or\nders, padlocked the doors leading\ninto the huge warehouse where the\nvats, of 2,000 gallons capacity each,\nare stored. Commissioner Brown\nstated the warehouse will remain\npadlocked until the disposition of\nthe case against the Silva brothers\nIn the United States district court.\nBrown declared that in the event\nof a conviction the government will\nbecome the owner of the wine and\nmay put it to legal use.\nAirmen Heroes of Arctic End Last\nFlight; Bodies Are Brought \u2018Home*!\nFAIRBANKS. Alaska. March\n7 (45\u2014The last flight of Lieu\ntenant Carl Ben Eielson and\nEarl Borland ended here today\nwhen Russian and American\nplanes, escorting the bodies of\nthe two aviators killed on the\nArctic coasi of Siberia, circled\nover Fairbanks and landed in\nquick succession at the Alaska\nAirways field at 1:30 p. m. <3:30\npm.. P.C.T.).\nThe bodies were brought\nrrore than 1.000 miles from the\nmotorship Nanuk, IcebouCl in\nthe Arctic ocean near North\nCape. Siberia, the goal which\nHow Prison Life Has Aged Mooney\nJ mCT\nF Mid\n>W,\nzao i S\nMl aA\nw K\n<lO\nNEA San Francisco Bureau.\nThese two striking facial studies show Tom Mccney. as a labcr leader in San Francisco in 1916, and as\nhe appear? Uday, at 47, a waiter at the guards\u2019 me\u00bbs in San Quentin penitentiary, awaiting action on\nthe pleas for his pardon now before Governor C. C. Young, of California. Mbancy and Warren Billings\nwire sentenced to prison for the Preparedness Day bombing in which nine peisons were killed 14 years\nago. Even the judge who sentenced Mooney is now taking a leading part in the effort to get a pardon\nfor him. The state supreme court and the state advisory pardon board are delving into the records. A\ndecision is expected soon.\nMexican Atones on Gallows For,\nMurders; Doomed Map Callapses\nNavy Conference\nReconvenes; Pact\nWill Be Rushed\nAristide Briand Repre\nsents France As Arms\nMeet Resumes Tasks.\nLONDON. March 7 Prime\nMinister Ramsay MacDonald, buoy\nant in spirit but with his face show\ning the strain of bearing the double\nburden of disarmament negotiations\nand parliamentary duties, today re\nlaunched the London naval con\nference.\nThat load in seven weeks has put\ndeeper lines in the prime minis\nters strong face and left dark\nplaces under his eyes, but he is still\ncarrying on in strong fashion.\nUnder his chairmanship today\nthe five chief delegates\u2014with Aris\ntide Briand heading the French for\nPremier Tardieu\u2014gathered around\nthe conference table in St. James\u2019\npalace. They surveyed the work done\nand problems remaining, then\nplunged into the tasks of their in-\n(Continued on Page Five)\nNarcotic Bureau\nSought by Solon\nMeasure Proposed to Aid\nEnforcement of U. S.\nAnti-Drug Statutes.\nWASHINGTON, March 7 Ori\nCreation as separate bureau of nar\ncotics was urged teday before the\nhouse ways and means committee\nby Representative Porter, republi-i\ncan. Pennsylvania, who said it was]\nutterly impossible' 'to enforce the 1\nfederal narcotics act \"so long as it\nis treated as a step-sen ot prohibi\ntion.\" Enforcement of the drug\nlaws are delegated largely to the\nprohibition unit.\nthe two fliers failed to attain\nwhen they flew from Teller.\nAlaska, on November 9.\nOn the way here, planrs\nbringing the bodies stopped at\nTeller where they were storm\nbound severcl days, and then\nflew to Ruby via. Nome. The\nplaner, circled over Nome while\nfuneral services were being\nheld on the flying field, which\nwas 100 rough because of recent\nblizzards to atempt a landing.\nThey then continued their\nflight to Rubv to refuel.\nThe planes remained over\n(Continued on Page Five)\nDOUGLAS, ARIZONA, SATURDAY MORNING. MARCH 8, 1930.\nFLORENCE. Ariz.. March 7\nWalking bravely up a short flight\nof stairs to the gallows. Refugio\nMacias, who killed two men in a\njealous rage, went to his death at\nthe state prison here early today.\nEleven minutes after the trap was\nsprung he was pronounced dead.\nIt was the second execution in\nArizona during the last two weeks.\nMrs. Eva Dugan having paid the\nextreme penalty Feb. 21 for a mur\nder she committed at Tucson.\nBefore Macias on his trip to the\ngallows walked a priest who had\nadministered the last rites to the\ncondemned man.\nOthers Collapse\nAs Macias was led by the cell of\nRichard Nash Burrows. 19-year-old\nChicago youth under sentence of\n(Continued on Fage Five*\nPlot to Defeat\nFarm Aid Rumored\nLegge and Hyde to Re\nport to Senate; Probe\nof Group Threatened.\nWASHINGTON. March 7\nReporting a favorable outlook for\nstabilization of farm prices. Chair\nman L?gge of the farm board was\nasked today by the senate agricul\nture committee for his views on\nthe extent of the opposition to the\nnew farm relief program.\nChairman McNary of the commit\ntee requested him and Secretary\nHyde to report tomorrow on charges\nthat a worki-wide scheme is in\noperation to destroy the effective\nness of the newly created farm re\nlief organization.\nLegge and Hyde appeared before\nthe committee in connection with\nthe resolution of Senator Nye, re\npublican North Dakota, for an in\nvestigation of the administration of\nthe new farm act. The hearing was\nin executive session but it was un\nderstood at the capitol that the\ngovernment farm leaders looked un\nfavorably on the investigation at\nthis time.\nState Contests\nNorthcott Writ\nIn Death Appeal\nLOS ANGELES. March 7.\nDenying the contentions of Gordon\nStewart Northcott in his appeal\nfrom srtitence of death for the slay\ning of three young boys at his ranch\nnear Riverside. Cahi.. the state to\nday filed answer to the convicted\nyouth's opening brief.\nThe state meets Northcott's prin\ncipal contention, that he was denied!\nthe constitutional guarantee of\ncompetent legal representation with'\na statement that the defendant re\nfused the counsel of attorneys ap-\npointed for him and insisted on con- i\nducting his own case. The state\ncontends that the court did not\ndeny Northcott counsel. but de-,\nchned to allow both the defendant;\nat d his attorneys actively to en-1\ngate in the defense.\nDr. Cook, Author\nAnd Explorer. To\nGet Parole Soon\nAttorney General Ap\nproves Freedom for 65-\nYear-Old Adventurer.\nLEAVENWORTH. Kas., March 7\n\u2014Dr. Frederick A. Cook, whose\nvariegated career of physician, ex\nplorer. author, lecturer, and oil pro\nmoter w\u2019as interrupted by a four\nteen year sentence to Leavenworth\nfederal prison, is prepared to f-.ee\nthe woriu again at the age of 63.\nA recommended parole was ap\nproved today by Attorney General\nMitchell at Washington. As soon\nas it is received here, probably late\ntomorrow, or Sunday, the man who\nwon instant fame and later con\ndemnation by his announced dis\ncovery of the North Pole in 130 b.\nwill te released.\nHelped Doctor.\nConvicted of using the mails o\ndefraud in connection with an oil\nprodiKtion scneine at Fort Worm,\n(Continued on Page Five)\nIrony Claimed In\nAnti-Censor Plea\nNew Mexico Senator'\nFights Measure to De- j\nlete Imported Literature\nWASHINGTON. March 7 I\nSenator Cutting, republican. New\nMexico, in presenting a petition j\nsigned by more than 500 educators,\nscientists and authors, protesting\nagainst the censorship of imports\nof foreign book', explained in me\nsenate today that part cf the peti\ntion was written in sarcastic irony.\nHe referred to the suggestion that\nif congress saw fit to \u2018piotect\nAmerican citizens at large\" against j\nliterature considered immoral or\nharmful, it should create a com- I\nm.ssioa to make that lit>r;\u00bbture\navailable to \"mature students, edi\ntors and writers on foreign a.fairs.\nthe dcpait\u2019nent of state, members i\nof congress and other statesmen\nand scientists.'\nIsthmus Of Panama Is\nShaken By Earthquake;\nNo Damage Is Reported\nCOLON, Panama, March 7\nThe Isthmus of Panama was shaken\nat 10:40 p. m.. tonight by an earth\nquake lasting 45 seconds. It was\nthe worst tremor since 1914.\nSleepers in creaking frame houses:\nwere thrown int oa panic as their j\nbeds moved. Early reports were!\nthat there were no damages. Offi-.\ncials did not expect the tremor tol\naffect the canal.\n3 Hurt In\nCar Crash;\n1 May Die\nCalifornia Man Probably\nFatally Injured in Bis\nbee Highway Wreck.\nSpeeding Auto Struck\nCulvert On Highway\nTrio Hurled Through Top\nof Roadster by Force\nof Impact.\nW. O. Weeks, ref 'esentative\nof Cass Howaid Co., Los An\ngeles, hovered at death's door\nat the Calumet hospital last\nnight as the result of an auto\nmobile accident four miles west\nof Douglas on the Bisbee high\nway at 2:30 a. m. Friday, and\nC. L. Soper of the Western\nWholesale Drug company, Phoe\nnix, and 11. L. Read of the Los\nAngeles board of trade, were\nseriously but not fatally in\njured.\nThe trio were on their way to\nBisbee in Soper\u2019s car, a Chrysler\nroadster, almost new. They were\ntraveling at a high rate of speed,\nevidence at the accident indicated.\nThe car struck the concrete abut\nment and iron railing of a culvert\njust east of the old Hood ranch.\nThe machine rolled over several\ntimes. One front wheel and part\nof the running gear of the car\nwere torn away and landed 50\nyards away in a field at the side\nof the road.\nOne Unconscious\nRead was knocked unconscious\nwhile Soper was terribly bruised\nabout the race and head and ap\noarently sustained slight internal\ninjiries. Weeks sustained a frac\ntured skull among other injuries.\nHe bled freely and physicians hold\nalmost no hope for his recovery.\nHe was reported as barely holding\nhis own in an unconscious condi\ntion at a late hour last night.\nSomething of the face of the\nimpact of the accident may be un\nderstood from the finding of a\nheavy pocket case filled with new\npencils which one of the men had\ncarried in a pocket. Every pencil\nwas broken and crushed.\nSent to Hospital\nDeputy Sheriff O. A. Ash, as\nusual, in night accidents on the\nhighway, was summoned before\nanything was done for the injured\nand dying. The deputy summoned\nan ambulance which brought Read\nand Weeks to the Calumet hospital\nwhile Ash brought Soper, the least\nseriously injured, in his car.\n(Continued on Page Five)\nNaval Air Ace\nTo Quit Service\nAlford J. Williams Plans\nto Build Fastest Air\nplane in World.\nWASHINGTON, March 7\nLieut. Alford J. Williams, a navy\nracing pilot, today submitted his\nresignation from the service to\nbuild an airplane which will re\ncover the world's aviation speed\nrecord for the United States.\u201d\nOrders for sea duty, which were\nto become effective tomorrow for\nthree years, were revoked by navy\nofficials pending action on the res\nignation, which was placed in the\nhands of Admiral Richard Leigh,\nacting chief of operations.\nWilliams asked that the resigna\ntion go into effect two months\nfrom March 15 to take care of\naccumulated leaves of absence\nstanding to his credit.\nAcceptance of the resignation\nwould terminate 13 years of mili\ntary service during which Williams\nwrote a one-man record of achieve\nment in naval aviation matched\nonly by that of Lieut. James Doo\nlittle in air corps history. Doolit\ntle, a crack army flier, resigned\nrecently from that branch of the\nservice.\nStrange New Malady Has Paralytic\nCharacteristics: Alcohol Is Blamed\nOKLAHOMA CITY. March 7\n\u201945.\u2014A strange malady with\nparalytic characteristics, appar\nently caused originally bv the\ninking of poisoned liquor, to\nnight had placed about 40 vic\ntims in Oklahoma City hos\npitals, with probably as many\nmore receiving treatment in\ntheir homes.\nDr. W. H. Miles, city physi\ncian, who was called upon to\ncope with the outbreak, was\nseeking to determine the cause\nof the illness and whether the\ndisease was communisable.\nThe greater part of the vic-\nTEN PAGES TODA'\nWife Who Beat\nSteno Is Given\n90 Days In Jail\nCLARKSDALE\u2019, Miss., March\n7 \u2022>?).\u2014Mrs. K. A. Carney,\nclubwoman and wife of a\nClarksdale attorney, was con\nvicted today of assault and\nbattery, in connection with an\nattack on her husband's ste\nnographer, Miss Mae Ross, and\nwas fined SSOO and sentenced\nto 90 days in jail.\nMrs. Carney had been charged\nwith assault and battery with\nintent to kill, but the jury\nfound her guilty only of as\nsault and battery.\nThe state had argued that\nthe 53-year-old defendant had\nattacked Miss Ross without\nprovocation.\n\"We must protect our work\ning girls from unprincipled mar\nried men and jealous wives,\u201d\nshouted C. S. Loungino, county\nattorney.\nBodies of Flier\nAnd Pals Found\nIn Plane Wreck\nPilot Doles, Co-Pilot Bie\nber and Steward Slaton\nDied in Crash.\nVICTORVILLE, Cal., March 7\n(>P) \u2014Coroner A. W. U\u2019Ren of San\nBernardino county, and a jury to\nnight decided that the three mem\nbers of the crew found dead in the\nwreckage of a Western Air Express\nplane in the San Bernardino moun\ntains today, came to. their deaths\nin \"an accidental crash.\u2019\u2019\nLOS ANGELES, March 7. oD\u2014\n\"Lucky\u201d Jimmy Doles, veteran of\nthe air, and his two companions\nwere found today, wrapped in the\ntwisted metal of their red tri\nmotored transport at the bottom of\na 1000-foot deep canyon, high in the\nsnowbound San Bernardino moun\ntains.\nIn. the secluded chasm, where\ndeath had held them secretly for\n12 days, a group of grief-stricken\nfriends scrambled down the steep\nwalls and through the heavy timber\nand underbrush to find them after\na weary trek through the moun\ntains.\nExpected All Dead\nThe searchers had no' doubt of\nwhat lay before them when they\nset our from Victorville, on the\ndesert to the east of the mountain\nrange, late yesterday, for a few\nhours before Dudley Steele and\nMrs. Juanita Burns, airplane pilots,\nhad sighted the wreckage of the\nlost ship. There remained only to\nlearn what happened to the trio on\ntheir last fatal flight.\nFrom the mute evidence the\nsearchers found, it seemed that\nDoles, passenger pilot for the West\nern Air Express, and his mates, Co-\nPilot A. W. Bieber and Steward\nJohn W. Slaton had run afoul of a\nterrific windstorm while flying with\nout passengers from Kingman, Ariz.,\nto Los Angeles on February 23.\nSought Landing\nBuffeted about in their heavy\nplane \u00abs they neared the divide of\nthe mountain range. Doles realized\nthe futility of attempting to reach\nLos Angeles and banked about,\nspeeding for the desert to the east\n(Continued on Page Five)\nDoheny Ready To\nFace Bribe Trial\nOil Man Accused of Giv\ning SIOO,OOO to Former\nInterior Secretary.\nWASHINGTON, March 7 (>ri\u2014\nEdward L. Doheny, wealthy oil\noperator, came to Washington to\nday to go on trial Monday on a\ncharge of giving former Secretary\nof the Interior Fall a bribe of SIOO,-\n000 for awarding his company a\nlease to the Elk Hills naval oil re\nserve.\ntims lost the use of their feet\nand legs, and most of them\ntold Dr. Miles and Dr. E. Gold\nfain, a nerve specialist assisting\nhim, that their illness had fol\nlowed the drinking of alcoholic\nliquor. Several victims, how\never, including a chiropodist\nand a minister, denied they had\npartaken of liquor.\nThe chiropodist said he had\ntreated several victims when\ntheir feet became paralyzed,\nand attributed his own condi\ntion to contagion.\nNo deaths had been attrib\n(Continued on Page Five)\nMetal Market\nCopper quiet; electrolytic, spot and\nfuture 18. Iron quiet; unchanged.\nTin steady; spot and nearby 36.37;\nfuture 36.62. Lead easy; spot N. Y.\n5.75; East St. Louis 5.60. Zinc easy;\nEast St. Louis spot and future 5.00.\nAntimony 8.87.\nNumber 216\nReport By\nPresident\nEncourages\nNext 60 Days Should See\nReturn of Prosperity\nand Normalcy, Belief.\nJob Shortage Termed\nSeasonal By Hoover\nSecretaries Lamont and\nDavis Issue Joint State\nment; Details Given.\nWASHINGTON, March 7\n(AP) \u2014American business and\nindustry is now recovering from\nthe shock administered it by\nthe stock market collapse last\nfall. President Hoover believes,\nand within 60 days should be\nfree from the distressing after\nmath of unemployment which\nit brought.\nHe announced the conclusion to\nday after a study of commerce and\nlabor department reports bearing\non the situation, and a revie of\nthe results being attained by co\noperation of the heads of national\nenterprises whom he convened in\nWashington last Decerrijer to con\nsider possibilities of business stim\nulus.\nJob Shortage Seasonal\nSummarizing his conclusions for\nnewspaper correspondents, the\npresident said that unemployment\n\"amounting to distress\u201d had been\nconfined to 12 states, and was not\nmore than season in the other 36\nstates Low points of business and\nemployment had been passed in\nDecember and in early January, he\nadded, and had been followed by\nslow betterment. With maintenance\nof wage rates .with lower interest\nrates, and with enlarged capital\nbetterment expenditures by rail\nroads, utilities, and business gen\nerally, he said he looked tot the\nadvance of spring to restore nor\nmal prosperity. The president made\nhis statement after conferring with\nSecretaries Lamont and Davis.\n1921-22 Was Worse.\nIn a joint statement amplifying\nthe findings particularly as to em\nployment, Secretaries Lamont and\nDavis refused to fix a specific fig\nure for numbers out of work, but\nestimated it as between one-third\nand one-half the number of unem\nployed during 1921-22. Forces of\nrecovery, the cabinet members said,\nwere found to be steadily gaining\nstrength.\nlln congress, Representative John\nson, republican, Nebraska, raised\ntoday the proposal for starting ex\ntensive relief work in connection\nwith constructing flood reservoirs\nfor the Mississippi river and tribu-\n(Continued on Page Five)\nVeteran Jurist\nIs 89 Years Old\nOliver Wendell Holmes,\nPatriot and Justice, to\nObserve Birthday.\nWASHINGTON, March 7.\nThe grand old man of American\njurisprudence, Oliver Wendell\nHolmes, tomorrow will celebrate his\n89th birthday. A veteran of the\nCivil war on the union side, three\ntimes wounded, the justice seeming\nly is in better health than for sev\neral years. He is constant in the\ndischarge of his judicial duties, not\nhaving missed a session of the court\nduring the present term, and being\none of the court\u2019s most prolific\nmembers in the preparation and de\nlivery of opinions.\nFor several weeks during the\npresent term he was acting chief\njustice during the absence of Chief\nJustice Taft because of illness and\nfollowing his resignation, before\nChief Justice Hughes took a seat\non the bench.\nMr. Holmes is the oldest justice\never to serve on that distinguished\ncourt. About a year ago he passed\nthe record held up to that time\nby Chief Justice Taney, who died as\na member of the court in his 88th\nyear.\nSon Of Germany\u2019s\nEx-Crown Prince\nNow Is Air Pilot\nBUENOS AIRES. March 7 <*s\u2014\nFerdinand Hohenzollern, son\nof the former crown prince of\nGermany, was granted a license\ntoday as a third grade air pilot\nafter a successful test flight in the\nairdrome here.\nLouis Ferdinand, who since last\nyear has been employed at the Ford\nplant in Buenos Aires began taking\nliyinj lessons ar Hollywood, Cal.,\nn n-e than a yea ago. The exam\nining officials Fai J he was an ex\ncellent phot.","height":"26283","width":"20382"}}
